    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Fordham University occupies the former 100‑acre Rose Hill Manor, bought by Andrew Carrigan in 1838 and later sold to Bishop John Hughes.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4,
        5,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fordham%2C_Bronx"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The New York and Harlem Railroad began operating in 1841, linking Fordham to New York City and encouraging suburban villa growth.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.cityneighborhoods.nyc/fordham-manor"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In 1973, New York University sold its campus to the City University of New York, renaming it Bronx Community College.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        7
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.nyc.gov/site/bronxcb5/about/our-neighborhoods.page"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Fordham’s name traces back to 1666 when John Archer founded a freehold manor along the Bronx River.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.cityneighborhoods.nyc/fordham-manor"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Old Fordham Village still contains historic buildings, including the original manor house and other side structures from the 19th century.",
